metadata.description:
If you love soccer and if you love cars, Rocket League will appeal to you. There is an oversized football inviting you to give it a solid one in its butt but you do not use your foot to administer the propulsive impact. Instead you use the car.

Playing in an enclosed stadium you can maneuver the car as you like to manipulate the ball and deliver a thumping sock to drive it home into the goal and score points. Cars have no hands so there is no question of handball!¬† Talking of hands and throw in from sidelines, the question simply does not arise as the ball keeps bouncing around from the sidewalls. The annoying referee is absent so presumably there are no fouls.

Should you feel in a vengeful mood you can flatten and destroy other vehicles that stand in your way and, surprise, you get reward points instead of a red card.¬† There are other things you can do that will get you reward points. For instance, if the opposition sends a ball rocketing into the goal and you zoom in and leap to save it, you get points.

Do you go it alone? In a sense, yes but there are helpers who nudge the ball towards you so that you can head it into the roof of the net. Start playing and you will immerse yourself in this fast moving game.


See more:¬†https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=njXBoViiJUU

metadata.creator: Beyond2000
metadata.description:
Rocket Robin Hood leads his "Merry Men", including the strong, dimwitted, and likeable Little John; consummate overeater Friar Tuck (who designs all the Merry Men's weaponry); Robin's two-fisted, red-headed cousin Will Scarlet; Robin's plucky girlfriend Maid Marian; his sharp-witted right-hand man Alan-a-Dale; the scrawny, feisty camp cook Giles (a reformed crook and Gabby Hayes
type); and other characters from the classic story of Robin Hood. They
live in "the astonishing year 3000" on New Sherwood Forest Asteroid, and
are determined to foil the despotic plans of Prince John and his
bumbling lackey, the Sheriff of N.O.T.T. (National Outer-space
Terrestrial Territories), and other villains such as Dr. Medulla, Manta,
Nocturne, and the Warlord of Saturn. Rocket Robin Hood and his people fly in spaceships and use weapons such as "electro-quarterstaffs".


Each 22 minute episode is divided into three segments, with
cliffhangers between the first and second part, and the second and third
part.


All episodes feature short vignettes of the various characters.


A male chorus sang the opening and the closing themes for each of the
three seasons of the cartoons, in the style of the old English ballads.
